            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Adina Becker-Yoo\u2019s life is a study in precision, much like the complex supply chains she manages. The only child of Korean immigrants, she was raised in the quiet suburbs of the East Bay, where her parents ran a successful dry-cleaning business. Their ethos was simple and unwavering: work diligently, value education, and build something tangible. This philosophy guided Adina to California Polytechnic State University, where she bypassed the flashier tech majors for a Bachelor's in Industrial Engineering, fascinated by the logic of how things are made and moved.\n\nHer career began in the late '90s, not in the glamorous world of software startups, but in the gritty, essential hardware sector. While others chased venture capital, Adina mastered inventory systems and optimized production lines. This steady focus allowed her to weather the dot-com bust and steadily climb the corporate ladder. The key turning point in her career was managing a massive product recall a decade ago; her calm, methodical leadership during the crisis cemented her reputation and led to her current role as Director of Hardware Operations.\n\nHer personal life found its counterbalance when she met Mark Becker, a thoughtful and witty landscape architect, at a friend's dinner party. Their union was a blending of worlds\u2014logic and art, systems and nature\u2014symbolized by their hyphenated name. They settled in San Francisco\u2019s Sunset District, raising their daughter, Chloe, who is now away at college studying journalism.\n\nAdina\u2019s connection to San Francisco is rooted in this domestic stability. Her 7.8-mile commute takes her from the foggy, residential calm of her neighborhood to the industrial parks of South San Francisco. Her days are a demanding mix of international calls and high-stakes problem-solving, but she finds release in the drive home, listening to history podcasts. Weekends are for walking through Golden Gate Park with Mark, exploring the city\u2019s endless culinary scene, or simply enjoying the quiet of her backyard. At 50, her aspirations have shifted. The drive for the next promotion has been replaced by a desire to mentor young women in STEM and a dream of extended travel with Mark. Adina\u2019s ambition is no longer about building a career, but about perfecting the well-engineered life she has so carefully constructed."
        },
